## Top-level field values

| attribute | constraints |
|---|---|
| `name` | Required. 1-255 characters. Unique across skills. |
| `description` | Optional. Up to 2000 characters. Short purpose line shown in `list_skills`. |
| `body` | Required. Non-empty markdown (see [The `body` field](#the-body-field) below). |
| `agent_types` | Optional. Set of agent type values (see [`agent_types` values](#agent_types-values)). Omit, `null`, or `[]` all mean "no restriction"; clearing a previously-set restriction is supported. |
| `resource_types` | Optional. Set of resource-type descriptor keys (see [`resource_types`](#resource_types)). Omit, `null`, or `[]` all mean "no restriction"; clearing is supported. |
| `is_enabled` | Optional + Computed. Boolean. Defaults to `true`. |
| `id` | Computed. Integer skill ID. |
| `is_builtin` | Computed. See [Builtin skills](#builtin-skills). Always `false` for skills created by this resource. |
| `created_at` | Computed. Creation timestamp. |
| `updated_at` | Computed. Last update timestamp. |

### The `body` field

`body` is free-form **markdown** — a platform brief / playbook the agent loads
on demand. It is surfaced to agents through the `list_skills` and `load_skill`
tools. The body may contain **Jinja2 template variables** (`{{ "{{ variable }}" }}`)
that the backend substitutes at prep time (for example a resource name or the
current date). Because it is markdown, write it with a heredoc (`<<-EOT ... EOT`)
rather than `jsonencode(...)`.

### `agent_types` values

`agent_types` restricts skill **discovery** to the listed agent types. When set
to `null` (the default — achieved by **omitting** the attribute) the skill is
discoverable by agents of any type. Each value must be a valid agent type:

| agent_type | meaning |
|---|---|
| `chat` | User-defined chat agents |
| `background` | User-defined background agents |
| `builtin_chat` | The builtin chat agent (MisterShell-managed) |
| `builtin_background` | The builtin background agent (MisterShell-managed) |
| `builtin_quick_action` | The builtin quick-action agent (MisterShell-managed) |
| `builtin_session_assist` | The builtin session-assist agent (MisterShell-managed) |

All six are valid filter values here regardless of whether you manage agents of
that type yourself.

> **Omit vs. empty list.** The backend canonicalizes an empty list to `null`
> ("unrestricted"), and the provider preserves whichever form you configured, so
> **omitting the attribute and setting `agent_types = []` are equivalent** and
> both round-trip cleanly. Clearing a previously-set restriction (by omitting
> the attribute or setting `[]`) is fully supported.

### `resource_types`

`resource_types` restricts skill **discovery** to agents operating on the listed
resource-type descriptor keys (e.g. `linux`, `cisco_ios`, `kubernetes_cluster`,
`aws_account`). When `null` (omitted) the skill is offered for any resource type.

- This is a **discovery filter only — not an authorization gate.** It controls
  whether the skill is *offered* to an agent; it does not grant or restrict any
  access.
- Values are validated by the backend against its resource-type **registry** at
  save time (an unknown key is rejected). They are **not** `OneOf`-validated by
  the provider, so the authoritative list is whatever your MisterShell instance's
  registry supports.
- The same **omit vs. `[]`** equivalence as `agent_types` applies: an empty list
  is canonicalized to `null` server-side and the provider preserves your
  configured form, so omitting the attribute and passing `[]` both mean "all
  types" and clearing is supported.

## Builtin skills

MisterShell ships a set of **builtin** skills (`is_builtin = true`) seeded from
the backend skill registry. They are projections of code: they are **re-synced
from the registry on every startup**, so any out-of-band edit to their content is
reverted.

- They **cannot be created or deleted** through this resource (the backend
  returns `403 Forbidden` on delete).
- Only their **`is_enabled`** flag is mutable server-side. Attempting to change
  `name`, `description`, `body`, `agent_types`, or `resource_types` of a builtin
  skill returns `403 Forbidden` (those fields are frozen by the registry).
- Because they are read-only in practice, manage them through the
  [`mistershell_ai_skill` data source](../data-sources/ai_skill.md) rather than
  this resource. `is_builtin` on any skill created by this resource is always
  `false`.

A representative set of builtin skills (the per-platform briefs) is:

| builtin skill name | resource_types |
|---|---|
| `cisco-ios-platform-brief` | `cisco_ios`, `cisco_iosxe` |
| `cisco-nxos-platform-brief` | `cisco_nxos` |
| `cisco-sdwan-edge-platform-brief` | `cisco_iosxe_sdwan` |
| `cisco-sdwan-vmanage-platform-brief` | `cisco_vmanage` |
| `cisco-sdwan-vsmart-platform-brief` | `cisco_vsmart` |
| `cisco-sdwan-vbond-platform-brief` | `cisco_vbond` |
| `cisco-ise-platform-brief` | `cisco_ise` |
| `panos-platform-brief` | `panos_ssh` |
| `infoblox-platform-brief` | `infoblox_nios` |
| `linux-platform-brief` | `linux` |
| `windows-platform-brief` | `windows` |
| `kubernetes-platform-brief` | `kubernetes_cluster` |
| `aws-platform-brief` | `aws_account` |
| `azure-platform-brief` | `azure_subscription` |
| `database-platform-brief` | `database` |
| `generic-ssh-platform-brief` | `generic_ssh` |

The builtin platform briefs are scoped to the `builtin_session_assist` and
`builtin_quick_action` agent types. This list is instance- and version-dependent
(it is seeded from backend code); query your instance with the data source for
the authoritative set.

## The `is_builtin` computed field

`is_builtin` reports whether MisterShell manages the skill from its registry. It
is **always `false`** for skills created by this resource, and it cannot be set —
the backend assigns it. Use it (via the data source) to tell apart admin-authored
custom skills from registry-seeded ones.

